  ### ExpressionEvaluator
   debugging into the JANINO libraries. Use one of the features, e.g. the "expression evaluator", in your program: import org.codehaus.janino.*; ExpressionEvaluator ee = new ExpressionEvaluator(); ee.cook("3 + 4"); System.out.println(ee.evaluate()); // Prints "7". Compile, run, ... be happy! Examples The <a href="https://github.com/janino-compiler/janino/blob/master/commons-compiler/src/main/java/org/codehaus/commons/c
  
  ### ScriptEvaluator
  href="#janino-as-a-script-evaluator" aria-hidden="true"> Janino as a Script Evaluator Analogously to the expression evaluator, a ScriptEvaluator API exists that compiles and processes a Java "block", i.e. the body of a method. If a return value other than "void" is defined, then the block must return a value of that type. As a special feature, it allows methods to be declared. The place and order of the method declarations is not relevant. Example: package foo; impor
  
  ### SimpleCompiler
  -a-simple-compiler" class="anchor" href="#janino-as-a-simple-compiler" aria-hidden="true"> Janino as a Simple Compiler The SimpleCompiler compiles a single .java file ("compilation unit"). Opposed to normal Java compilation, that compilation unit may declare more than one public type. Example: // This is file "Hello.java", but it could have any name. public class Foo { public static void main(String[] args) { new Bar().meth(); } } public class Bar { public void 
  
  ### dependencies
  "anchor" href="#requirements" aria-hidden="true"> Requirements JANINO only requires a Java 7 (or later) JRE or later, not a JDK. It has no dependencies whatsoever on any third-party libraries. JANINO is routinely tested against the following JREs: Java version JRE version Release Date Status 7 jdk1.7.0_21 (32 bit) 2011-07-28 passed 8 adopt_openjdk-8.0.292.10-hotspot ?
  
  ### commons-compiler
   href="https://repo1.maven.org/maven2/org/codehaus/janino/janino/">the latest version of "janino- version .jar" . Download the same version of "commons-compiler- version .jar" . Put the two JAR files on your classpath. Security / integrity All packages are signed with one of these PGP keys. Make sure to check the package 
  
  ### Janino
   Janino by janino-compiler </script
